{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}} {{Use British English|date=September 2016}} {{Infobox person | name = Des Dearlove | image = Des Dearlove.jpg | alt = Des Dearlove | caption = Des Dearlove | other_names = Dearlove, Desmond | occupation = American business theorist | birth_date = 1960s | birth_place = }}
'''Desmond (Des) Dearlove''' (born 1960s) is a British management journalist and business theorist, known for his work on the history and state of the art of management theory.<ref>Jackson, Brad. ''Management gurus and management fashions: A dramatistic inquiry.'' Psychology Press, 2001.</ref><ref>Mullins, Laurie J. ''Management and organisational behaviour.'' Pearson Education, 2007.</ref><ref>Huczynski, Andrzej. ''Management gurus.'' Routledge, 2012.</ref>
Dearlove obtained his BSc in Politics And Economics at the [[University of Southampton]] in 1986. In the late 1980s he started as columnist for ''[[The Times]]'' and worked as business journalist, editor and ghost writer. From 1999 he co-founded Suntop Media Ltd. With [[Stuart Crainer]] he cofounder of the Thinkers50 management initiative.
== Selected publications == * [[Crainer, Stuart]], and Des Dearlove. ''Gravy training: Inside the business of business schools.'' Jossey-Bass Publishers, 1999. * Crainer, Stuart, and Des Dearlove. ''Generation Entrepreneur: Shape Today's Business Reality, Create Tomorrow's Wealth, Do Your Own Thing.'' FT Press, 2000. * [[Crainer, Stuart]], and Des Dearlove, eds. ''Financial Times handbook of management.'' Pearson Education, 2004. * Dearlove, Des. ''[http://www.1insaat.com/uploads/TrbBlogs/pdfs_3/36549_1223924831_604.pdf Business the Richard Branson way: 10 secrets of the world's greatest brand builder].'' Vol. 24. John Wiley & Sons, 2007. * Dearlove, Des. ''The Unauthorized Guide to Doing Business the Bill Gates Way: 10 Secrets of the World's Richest Business Leader.'' John Wiley & Sons, 2010.
Articles, a selection: * Dearlove, Des. "Key management decisions." ''Financial Times,'' London (1998). * Dearlove, Des. "[http://bsr.london.edu/files/365/BUSR315.pdf Interview: Jeff Skoll]." ''Business strategy review'' 15.2 (2004): 51-53.
