''' Henry Ludington ''' (May 25, 1739 – January 24, 1817) was an American businessman who ran a [[grist mill]] and owned a substantial parcel of land in [[New York (state)|New York state]]. He founded Ludingtonville, which later became the town of [[Kent, New York]].  He was a citizen of [[Patterson, New York]], and was involved with its growth.

Ludington fought in the [[Seven Years' War]] and, as captain, commanded a volunteer regiment at the [[Battle of Ridgefield]] during the [[American Revolutionary War]]. Ludington was promoted to Colonel and became an [[aide-de-camp]] to [[General officer|General]] [[George Washington]] in providing spies for [[espionage]]. He was associated with [[John Jay]] in a ring of spies. His daughter [[Sybil Ludington]] is well known to historians for her role in the [[American Revolution]] in helping the cause for independence by undertaking a nighttime horseback ride similar to that done by the patriot [[Paul Revere]] to alert the colonial militia to the approach of [[British Armed Forces|British forces]].

Ludington's descendants have continued his legacy in several states besides [[New York (state)|New York]], including [[Wisconsin]] and [[Michigan]]. Some became leaders in their own right and others were involved in developing towns.

== Ancestry ==

Ludington's great-great-grandfather William Ludington (b. 1608) and his wife Ellen (b. 1617) were of English origin. Their places of birth in England are unknown. They were married in England in 1636. A few years later they immigrated to America. William and Ellen moved permanently to [[Charlestown, Massachusetts]], in 1640 and raised seven children (one had been born in England).{{sfn|Johnson|1907|p=18}} William and his wife are the founders of the Ludington family in America and many of their descendants are in the [[Eastern United States]].{{sfn|Johnson|1907|p=19}} William and Ellen moved to [[New Haven, Connecticut]], about 1660.{{sfn|Johnson|1907|p=9}} It is recorded by 20th-century historian Louis S. Patrick that William died in 1663 at East Haven.{{sfn|Patrick|1907|p=265}} By other historians his death is recorded as occurring in 1662.{{sfn|Pelletreau|1886|p=691}} The difference in dating is due to the use the [[Julian Calendar]] in the mid-18th century in the [[Thirteen Colonies]] in America.{{sfn|Johnson|1907|p=10}}

The sixth child of William, founder of the American Ludingtons, was another William Ludington (second in family) who was born about 1655 (died 1737). His first wife was Martha Rose and they had two sons and a daughter. Their first child was a Henry Ludington, who was born in 1679. The second child of this Henry Ludington was still another William Ludington, born in [[Branford, Connecticut]], on September 6, 1702. He married Mary Knowles November 5, 1730, and they had eight children. Their third child was named Henry Ludington; his uncles were [[Patriot (American Revolution)|patriots]] and fought in one way or another for American independence.{{sfn|Johnson|1907|pp=20–21}}

