{{Infobox person | name = Jamal al Barzinji | image = JAlbarzinji.jpg | alt = | caption = Jamal al Barzinji in 2011 | birth_name = <!-- only use if different from name --> | birth_date = {{Birth date|mf=yes|1939|12|15}} | birth_place = [[Mosul, Iraq]] | death_date = {{death date and age|2015|09|26|1939|12|15}} | death_place = | nationality = Iraqi American | other_names = | occupation = | years_active = | known_for = | notable_works = }}
'''Jamal al Barzinji''' ({{lang-ar|جمال برزنجي}}) (December 15, 1939 – September 26, 2015) was an [[Iraqis|Iraqi]]-[[United States|American]] [[businessman]], associated with the [[International Institute of Islamic Thought]], the [[World Assembly of Muslim Youth]], and the [[SAAR Foundation]].
He was a founder and served on the board of the [[Islamic Society of North America]] and is a past president of the [[Muslim Students' Association]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=VJj8voB723YC&pg=PA287] </ref>
==Background== Barzinji was listed as the successor registrant of [[Grover Norquist]]'s defunct [[lobbying firm]] [[Janus-Merritt Strategies]], after the departure of [[David Safavian]].<ref>[http://www.madison.com/post/blogs/dailybriefing/55272 Good-Bye David Safavian]{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
On September 25, 2011 Barzinji was awarded a lifetime achievement award by the Arab community of northern Virginia at an event attended by Virginia governor [[Tim Kaine]].
Barzinji died on September 26, 2015.<ref>[http://www.counterpunch.org/2015/09/29/dr-jamal-barzinji-1939-2015-in-memoriam/ Dr. Jamal Barzinji (1939-2015): In Memoriam by Sami Al-Arian]</ref>
