{{BLP sources|date=August 2009}} {{Infobox basketball biography | name = Žarko Zečević | image = | caption = | league = | team = | number = | position = [[Center (basketball)|Center]] | height_m = | weight_kg = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1950|01|19}} | birth_place = [[Belgrade]], [[People's Republic of Serbia|PR Serbia]], [[Federal People's Republic of Yugoslavia|FPR Yugoslavia]] | nationality = [[Serbia]]n | highschool = | college = | draft_league = | draft_year = | draft_team = | career_start = 1966 | career_end = 1977 | years1 = 1966–1977 | team1 = [[KK Partizan|Partizan]] | awards = | medal_templates = {{MedalSport|Men's basketball}} {{MedalCountry|{{bkw|YUG}}}} {{MedalCompetition|[[Basketball at the Mediterranean Games|Mediterranean Games]]}} {{MedalGold|[[Basketball at the 1971 Mediterranean Games|1971 Izmir]]|[[Basketball at the 1971 Mediterranean Games|Team]]}} {{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship|European Championship for Juniors]]}} {{MedalSilver| [[1968 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship|1968 Spain]] | Team}} }}
'''Žarko Zečević''' ({{lang-sr-cyr|italic=yes|Жарко Зечевић}}, born 19 January 1950 in [[Belgrade]], [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|SFR Yugoslavia]]) is a Serbian retired basketball player, former football administrator, and current businessman. Known by his widely used nickname '''Zeka''', he is most notable as the controversial and all powerful general-secretary of [[FK Partizan]], a role he performed for more than two decades.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Press Online|author=STANIĆ, M.|title=Žarko Zečević: KUNEM SE, POVLAČIM SE!|url=http://www.pressonline.rs/sr/vesti/sport/story/14005/%C5%BDarko+Ze%C4%8Devi%C4%87:+KUNEM+SE,+POVLA%C4%8CIM+SE!.html|language=Serbian|date=21 June 2007}}</ref> Since 2007, he is employed at [[YugoRosGaz]], a subsidiary of [[Gazprom]].
Born to Slavko Zečević (former Police Minister and former [[FK Partizan]] managing board member) Žarko's entire sports career, both playing and administrative, is also tied to [[Partizan Belgrade|Partizan Sports Society]]. During the late 1960s and 1970s, he was a basketball player for [[KK Partizan]] and even managed 16 appearances in the Yugoslavia national basketball team jersey, though only in friendly preparation games and minor competitions - he never made the final cut for any of the major competitions (Eurobasket, World Championships, and the Olympics).
==Personal== Žarko Zečević is married to Mira who used to work as marketing director at ''[[Politika]]'' daily newspaper during the 1990s. They have a son and a daughter.
Zečević's sister is married to Danko Đunić, former Partizan Sports Society president.
